  "overview": {
    "title": "Jak masz na imię?",
    "duration": "45 minutes",
    "objectives": [
      "Greet and say goodbye (formal and informal)",
      "Ask and answer ‘What is your name?’ (Jak masz na imię? / Jak się nazywasz?)",
      "Ask and answer ‘How are you?’ (Jak się masz? / Co słychać?)",
      "Conjugate and use basic forms of ‘być’ (to be) and ‘mieć’ (to have)",
      "Use basic personal pronouns in the nominative case (ja, ty, on, ona, pan, pani)",
      "Learn numbers 0–10"
    ],
    "cultural_notes": [
      "Use 'Cześć' in informal situations; 'Dzień dobry' in formal or professional settings.",
      "Refer to strangers or superiors with 'pan' (sir) or 'pani' (ma'am) to show respect.",
      "It’s polite to offer a firm handshake and maintain eye contact when meeting someone.",
      "'Dzień dobry' is used until late afternoon; after that, 'Dobry wieczór' is used.",
      "Common polite expressions include 'Przepraszam' (Excuse me/Sorry), 'Proszę' (Please), and 'Dziękuję' (Thank you)."
    ],
    "difficulty": "beginner"
  },
  "grammar_insight": {
    "explanation": "In this lesson, we focus on greetings, introducing oneself, and basic verbs. To ask someone’s name informally: ‘Jak masz na imię?’. Formally: ‘Jak ma pan/pani na imię?’. Basic pronouns include: ja (I), ty (you informal), on (he), ona (she), pan/pani (you formal). Verbs być (to be) and mieć (to have) in the singular. ‘Jak się masz?’ or ‘Co słychać?’ is used to ask ‘How are you?’. Possible answers: świetnie, bardzo dobrze, dobrze, tak sobie, źle, fatalnie.",
